            <lb/>A M E N
             <cb/>
         <lb/> Following the effects of the Body of
         <lb/> Christ. <emphasis> Just as it was said by Reymundus:
         <lb/> "This sacrament
         <lb/> of the Body of Chrit accomplishes
         <lb/> enetrnity and immortality
         <lb/> for those who take it worthy, and the opposite [for those who don't]" </emphasis>
         <lb/> <emphasis> The Apostle [says]:
         <lb/> "Let a man examine himself
         <lb/> and thus is understood what is said. Carefully
         <lb/> consider what is served to you
         <lb/> certainly such as the host of Christ." </emphasis> Hence
         <lb/> the verse: <emphasis> White, wheaten, thin
         <lb/> not large, round,
         <lb/> without yeast, not
         <lb/> false, the host of Christ should be. </emphasis> Gloss:
         <lb/> <i>White:</i> signifies chastity,
         <lb/> thus you should be white
         <lb/> that is chaste in body and heart.
         <lb/> <i>Wheaten:</i> wheat is the sweetest
         <lb/> of all grain, so you should
         <lb/> be sweet and gentle.
         <lb/> <i>Thin</i>: that is moderate in food
         <lb/> and drink. <i>Not large:</i> that is
         <lb/> humble, not proud. <i>Round:</i> such as
         <lb/> a round shape is moveable so
         <lb/> you should be moveable for the divine
         <lb/> office and for [doing certain] good
         <lb/> deeds. <i>Without yeast:</i>
         <lb/> yeast signifies envy and
      <cb/>
         <lb/> anger, that is [you] should
         <lb/> have a [sincere heart] for God and the close ones
         <lb/> of yours. <i>Not false:</i> that is without
         <lb/> greed and avarice. <emphasis> Hence
         <lb/> Jerome [says]: I do not remember having read
         <lb/> of anyone being damned who
         <lb/> in this world led a life
         <lb/> [that was] decent. That is [to have a] great will
         <lb/> to work and so on. </emphasis> <emphasis> Following
         <lb/> as Ecclesiasticus says: [Who] worthily
         <lb/> takes the sacrament
         <lb/> receives thirteen blessings. </emphasis>
         <lb/> <emphasis> Hence the verse: I increase, I mingle, I sooth
         <lb/> I restrain, I terrify, I cleanse
         <lb/> I ignite, I enlighten, I double
         <lb/> I strengthen, I draw near, I lead, and
         <lb/> I give life. Upon the table so many dishes
         <lb/> I place. </emphasis> Gloss: <i>I increase:</i>
         <lb/> namely grace in the present and glory
         <lb/> in the future. <i>I mingle:</i> that is I [make one] gentler
         <lb/> <i>I sooth:</i> namely temptations.
         <lb/> <i>I reastrain:</i> that is evil
         <lb/> affection and the desire of the flesh.
         <lb/> <i>I terrify:</i> namely demons, for nothing
         <lb/> do the demons fear more
         <lb/> than the Body of Christ. <emphasis> Hence
         <lb/> Chrystostomus says: The Body of Christ repels
         <lb/> demons and calls angels </emphasis>
      <cb/>
         <lb/> and rightly so, because where [their] Lord
         <lb/> is, his agnels are [too].
         <lb/> <i>I cleanse:</i> namely venial sins.
         <lb/> <i>I ignite:</i> namely [your] affection and spirit
         <lb/> toward good. <i>I enlighten:</i>
         <lb/> namely your understating. <i>I double:</i>
         <lb/> that is I multiply merit here
         <lb/> and merit there. <i>I strengthen:</i> namely
         <lb/> the virtues [within] you. <i>I draw near:</i> that is
         <lb/> I shall be familiar in [your] soul.
         <lb/> <i>I lead:</i> namely out of misery
         <lb/> and mourning to joy.
         <lb/> <i>I give:</i> namely eternal life.
         <lb/> A M E N
         </p>
